Source: Philippine Statistics Authority
Cordillera has the least number of persons with
disability (PWD)

The Philippines had a household population of 92.1 million in 2010. Of which
1.44 million or 1.57 percent had a disability. Table 1 shows that CAR had the
least number of person with disability (PWD) across the country. There were
26 thousand PWDs recorded in CAR, which is 1.63 percent of its household
population, higher than the national level (1.57 percent).

 In Cordillera, the highest population with disability was in Benguet with
5,507 PWDs, followed by Abra with 4,357. Meanwhile, Apayao had the least
with number with 2,419. However, Apayao posted the highest proportion of
PWDs to household population with 2.15 percent, higher than that of the region
with 1.63 percent.
More males with disability
 Of the total PWDs in CAR, 52.2 percent were males and the rest were females.
This means that there were 109 male PWDs for every 100 female PWDs.

 Males outnumbered females in the age group 0 to 64 years. The largest
difference in the number of males was in the age group 15 to 49 years with a sex
ratio of 130 males per 100 females. In the age group 65 years and over, more
females had disabilities than males with a sex ratio of 72 males for every
100 females.


Across the provinces, the highest excess in the number of males was in Benguet
with a sex ratio of 119 males in every 100 females. Apayao placed second with
116 males in every 100 females. In Abra, females were almost at a par with
males, having a sex ratio of 101.

 Of the total 26,312 PWD in CAR, 64.8 percent (17,043) were Roman Catholics,
distantly followed by Evangelicals with 7.9 percent (2,085) and Non-Roman
Catholic and Protestant with 7.4 percent (1,948).
High number of PWD aged 5 years and over were primary undergraduate
 In 2010, a total of 24,962 PWDs aged 5 years and over were recorded in the
region. Of which, 30.2 percent (7,548) were primary undergraduate,
20.3 percent (5,056) had no grade completed, and 11.2 percent (2,808) were
high school graduate. Only 7.8 percent (1,941) had college degrees.

PSA-CAR Special Release: Persons with Disability
Disability - is an impairment that may be cognitive, developmental, intellectual, mental,
physical, sensory, or some combination of these, and that substantially affects a person's life
activities.
Religious affiliation - is the self–identified association of a person with a religion, denomination
or sub–denominational religious group.
Household - a social unit consisting of a person living alone or a group of persons who sleep
in the same housing unit and have a common arrangement in the preparation and consumption
of food.
Household Head – an adult person, male or female who is responsible for the organization and
care of the household, or who is regarded as such by the members of the household.
Household Population – comprises of persons who belong to a household.
Post Baccalaureate – refers to any course for which an undergraduate is required.
Post-Secondary – refers to the stage of formal education following the secondary education
level covering nondegree programs that have varying duration lasting up to three years.
Proportion - a part, share, or number considered in comparative relation to a whole.
